    translation: "An effect becomes a cause, and a cause becomes an effect. But Brahman, the eternal Reality, is neither effect nor cause.",
    commentary: "This verse employs causal analysis to discriminate between Brahman and the world. In the realm of manifestation, everything is part of a cause-effect chain: the pot (effect) becomes a cause when used to carry water; water (cause of satisfaction) becomes an effect of rain. This endless chain characterizes the relative world—nothing is absolutely independent; everything depends on something else. This very dependence proves its unreality as an independent entity. Brahman, however, transcends this chain entirely. It is neither caused by anything (so it's not an effect/karya) nor does it produce anything in the ultimate sense (so it's not a cause/karana). It simply IS—uncaused existence. Why? Because Brahman is Existence itself, not an existing thing. The wave is caused, but water simply is. Similarly, the world-appearance has apparent causation, but Brahman, the substratum, is causeless. This understanding is crucial: if you seek what is truly real and independent, discard everything in the cause-effect chain and rest in the causeless Consciousness.",
